{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-blog-post-js","path":"/2018-06-23-debugging-3/","result":{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"John D Potts","author":"John Potts"}},"markdownRemark":{"id":"73045565-c405-53aa-ad48-04854c7b0cf0","html":"<p>\n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/2b270b0a3b988fd9626bf5672842b510/887cb/debugging3.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block;  max-width: 420px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 66.66666666666666%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;\"\n        alt=\"Debugging\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/2b270b0a3b988fd9626bf5672842b510/65f94/debugging3.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/2b270b0a3b988fd9626bf5672842b510/d2682/debugging3.jpg 105w,\n/static/2b270b0a3b988fd9626bf5672842b510/60342/debugging3.jpg 210w,\n/static/2b270b0a3b988fd9626bf5672842b510/65f94/debugging3.jpg 420w,\n/static/2b270b0a3b988fd9626bf5672842b510/828fb/debugging3.jpg 630w,\n/static/2b270b0a3b988fd9626bf5672842b510/bba1f/debugging3.jpg 840w,\n/static/2b270b0a3b988fd9626bf5672842b510/887cb/debugging3.jpg 4134w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 420px) 100vw, 420px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<p>Debugging javascript errors in a webpage or application can be incredibly tedious and time-consuming; even more so if you’re not using the right tools.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"js\">\n      <pre class=\"language-js\"><code class=\"language-js\">console<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">log</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>myObject<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\nconsole<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">log</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token keyword\">this</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\nconsole<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">log</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token string\">'ARGGGGGGHHHHH'</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span></code></pre>\n      </div>\n<p>If the above snippet looks familiar, it’s time for you to become better acquainted with the JS debugging capabilities of Chrome Dev Tools.</p>\n<p>This post is certainly not exhaustive, but I will hit on a few key things that you should know are available to you when debugging on the front end.</p>\n<p>First of all, the console api has quite a few more methods available than the plain <code class=\"language-text\">console.log()</code>.</p>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Method</th>\n<th>Result</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><code class=\"language-text\">console.table()</code></td>\n<td>outputs a table detailing properties of an object</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><code class=\"language-text\">console.info()</code></td>\n<td>outputs an informational log</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><code class=\"language-text\">console.warn()</code></td>\n<td>outputs a warning log</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><code class=\"language-text\">console.error()</code></td>\n<td>outputs an error log</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><code class=\"language-text\">console.assert()</code></td>\n<td>makes an assertion that evaluates to <code class=\"language-text\">true</code> or <code class=\"language-text\">false</code></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><code class=\"language-text\">console.error()</code></td>\n<td>outputs an error log</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><code class=\"language-text\">console.error()</code></td>\n<td>outputs an error log</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><code class=\"language-text\">console.groupCollapsed()</code>/<code class=\"language-text\">console.groupEnd()</code></td>\n<td>outputs a collapsed group of console messages from console.log() statements in between</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><code class=\"language-text\">console.clear()</code></td>\n<td>clears out the console</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><code class=\"language-text\">console.count()</code></td>\n<td>outputs a count of the number of times the argument is called</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><code class=\"language-text\">console.time()</code>/<code class=\"language-text\">console.timeEnd()</code></td>\n<td>serves as a stopwatch for timing execution of code</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>But to see what’s happening in your script, you don’t have to put any console methods in your script. Simply putting in the line <code class=\"language-text\">debugger();</code> will cause the code to pause execution at that line when you have dev tools open.</p>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/0c8a2c4bb17ae64273fab4a5b266f333/11b93/debug-mode.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block;  max-width: 420px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 56.19047619047619%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;\"\n        alt=\"Debug Mode\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/0c8a2c4bb17ae64273fab4a5b266f333/d10fb/debug-mode.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/0c8a2c4bb17ae64273fab4a5b266f333/79c17/debug-mode.png 105w,\n/static/0c8a2c4bb17ae64273fab4a5b266f333/65ed1/debug-mode.png 210w,\n/static/0c8a2c4bb17ae64273fab4a5b266f333/d10fb/debug-mode.png 420w,\n/static/0c8a2c4bb17ae64273fab4a5b266f333/f058b/debug-mode.png 630w,\n/static/0c8a2c4bb17ae64273fab4a5b266f333/1e088/debug-mode.png 840w,\n/static/0c8a2c4bb17ae64273fab4a5b266f333/11b93/debug-mode.png 1124w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 420px) 100vw, 420px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<p>You can also set breakpoints from within dev tools. Right clicking an element will enable you to set breakpoints on that element’s attribute/subtree modifications or node removal. Additionally, you can view event listeners for the element under the ‘event listener’ tab in the elements pane.</p>\n<p>When your code is paused in debugging mode, you have a number of options available to you. You can resume code execution or choose to step through the code by function or line-by-line. You can set watch statements, which will show you the current value of variables that you enter in. You can also view the function call stack and the scope of your code (including what variables and methods are contained within the scope.)</p>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/3e688ad8ca35dc63ff40224a966469b3/8740f/script.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block;  max-width: 420px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 57.14285714285714%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;\"\n        alt=\"Source view\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/3e688ad8ca35dc63ff40224a966469b3/d10fb/script.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/3e688ad8ca35dc63ff40224a966469b3/79c17/script.png 105w,\n/static/3e688ad8ca35dc63ff40224a966469b3/65ed1/script.png 210w,\n/static/3e688ad8ca35dc63ff40224a966469b3/d10fb/script.png 420w,\n/static/3e688ad8ca35dc63ff40224a966469b3/f058b/script.png 630w,\n/static/3e688ad8ca35dc63ff40224a966469b3/1e088/script.png 840w,\n/static/3e688ad8ca35dc63ff40224a966469b3/8740f/script.png 1106w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 420px) 100vw, 420px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<p>You can do a great deal with breakpoints inside the JS debugging pane; you can choose to set more breakpoints on certain events, to pause on exceptions, or to clear all breakpoints.</p>\n<p>There are all kinds of options open in Chrome Dev tools to examine the execution of your Javascript files. Take advantage of them, and you’ll find debugging happens much more quickly!</p>\n<p>You can also choose to open the source JS files that are running on the page; you can make edits to these (but you’ll need to save them for the edits to take effect)</p>","excerpt":"Debugging javascript errors in a webpage or application can be incredibly tedious and time-consuming; even more so if you’re not using the…","fields":{"slug":"/2018-06-23-debugging-3/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Front End Debugging: Working with Javascript in Chrome Dev Tools","date":"June 23, 2018","recommended":null,"featuredImage":{"childImageSharp":{"fluid":{"src":"/static/2b270b0a3b988fd9626bf5672842b510/a7715/debugging3.jpg"}}}}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/2018-06-23-debugging-3/","previous":{"fields":{"slug":"/2018-06-16-debugging-2/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Front End Debugging: HTML and CSS"}},"next":{"fields":{"slug":"/2018-06-30-debugging-4/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Front End Debugging 4: Network Tab and More"}}}},"staticQueryHashes":["2913751889"]}